<br>
The cost of building reactors might not be recovered, it says.<br>
<br>
DOUG ABRAHMS<br>
Gannett News Service<br>
May 10, 2003<br>
<br>
WASHINGTON — An independent congressional agency said Friday that the risk of default by nuclear power plants built with federal loan guarantees would be greater than 50 percent, throwing cold water on a Senate proposal aimed at expanding U.S. nuclear power.<br>
<br>
The Congressional Budget Office issued a report saying the cost of building a nuclear generating plant is more than four times higher than a natural gas-fired facility, and the construction cost of a reactor might never be recovered. <br>
<br>
Under a provision in the Senate energy bill, the government would back atomic reactor construction loans up to 50 percent.<br>
<br>
“Because the cost of power from the first of the next generation of new nuclear power plants likely would be significantly above prevailing market rates, we would expect that the plant operations would default on the borrowing that financed its capital costs,” the CBO report said.<br>
<br>
The Nuclear Energy Institute, a trade association of utilities that wants to build 50 nuclear power plants by 2020 — said the CBO overestimated the cost of a new plant by 35 percent, said spokesman Steve Kerekes. <br>
<br>
Modular prototypes of nuclear power plants have been developed to cut construction and permitting costs, he said.<br>
<br>
“(CBO) is kind of locked into the view of where industry construction was 25 years ago, and that’s not where we are today,” Kerekes said.<br>
<br>
But even the industry’s cost estimate to build a nuclear power plant is three times higher than a natural gas-fired generator.<br>
<br>
The Bush administration, congressional Republicans and the energy industry want to build a new generation of U.S. atomic reactors over the next 20 years to increase electricity supplies and cut air pollution.<br>
<br>
Today, 103 operating nuclear power plants provide 21 percent of U.S. electricity, according to the Energy Department. But no commercial generator has been ordered by a utility since the early 1980s — in the aftermath of the Three Mile Island reactor malfunction that caused a release of radioactive gas in 1979.<br>
<br>
Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., opposed the nuclear provision during a committee meeting last month because of the potential bailout that the federal government might have to make. Wyden brought up the Washington Public Power Supply System, the Northwest utility that attempted to build five nuclear power plants in the 1980s before defaulting on $2 billion in loans and increasing electric rates.<br>
<br>
“My sense is we’re talking about billions of dollars” that the federal government might have to pay out if the loans default, he said.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
