What does the nuclear industry say? This is from the industry's trade group, the Nuclear Energy Institute (www.nei.org)<br>
<br>
From their essay:<br>
Three Mile Island: Myths and Facts<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The March 28, 1979, accident at Unit 2 of the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant in Pennsylvania spawned a handful of myths about the nuclear power industry. This document provides facts that belie the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>myths that often are perpetuated by<br>
groups opposed to nuclear power</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<br>
The Myth:<br>
The TMI accident caused a decline in America’s nuclear<br>
energy industry.<br>
The Facts:<br>
Notwithstanding the realitythat the accident hurt the nuclear energy industry’s public image, the practical reality is that<br>
Three Mile Island was the catalyst for significant institutional<br>
and operational changes that translated into dramatic improvements in plant safety and efficiency. After a one-year<br>
moratorium on plant licensing, while the industry and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission studied the accident, new<br>
nuclear power plants once again began to enter service. In fact, 41 percent (51 units) of the 123 commercial nuclear units licensed between 1959 and 1995 began operation after<br>
the accident<br>
...<br>
<br>
The Myth:<br>
The Three Mile Island accident caused electric utility<br>
companies to cancel large numbers of nuclear power plants.<br>
The Facts:<br>
The 111 nuclear plants canceled between 1974 and 1990 divide roughly in half between the pre-TMI years (51 units) and the post-TMI years (60 units).<br>
...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
