yale <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A> at: 6/11/03 7:26 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Liberty Ship's Creator</span><br>  Posts: 260<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/17/03 11:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=159.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Senate OKs Plan to Revive Nuclear Power </span><hr size=1> Yes, yales is right, TMI had a mostly peripheral effect on the nuclear power industry, despite the utterly hysterical over-reaction it engendered in the press and the public.<br>
<br>
No, what clobbered the nuclear power industry was a combination of the Arab Oil Embargo, which briefly slowed the growth of demand for electricity, the sky-high interest rates stagflation saddled us with, which vastly increased capital costs, and the US .gov, motivated by well-meaning but misguided Greens, who changed all of the rules about building nuclear plants in the middle.<br>
<br>
As a utility owner in the 70's, you don't need the baseline power as much as you thought you did, the .gov is dragging its feet and causing you years of delay on an already capital-intensive project, and interest rates are suddenly HUGE.<br>
<br>
Imagine adding a years interest on a billion dollar loan, at a rate of 15 percent.  That extra 150 million hurts.<br>
<br>
<br>
Nowadays, none of those issues remains.<br>
<br>
Stringent pre-licensing makes many of the delaying tactics of the anti's useless.  The rules and regulations about nuclear plants seem stable at last.  Modern plants are standardised designs built in pre-assembled modules, quick and easy to build.  And it is hard to imagine interest rates getting much lower, making the large capital costs of the nuke easier to bear.<br>
<br>
As an added note, technology is better now.  The AP-1000 can be built from groundbreaking to first fueling in 36 months, and with practice could be as fast as 24 months.  <br>
<br>
The AP-1000 is also vastly safer and cleaner than current designs.<br>
<br>
But the tech changes go deeper than the actual plants themselves.<br>
<br>
For example, every nuclear power plant built in the USA had the reactor pressure vessel skidded into place, a slow and expensive process.  Why?  Because even disassembled, the RPV was too heavy to move any other way.<br>
<br>
Nowadays, a new plants pressure vessel can be plucked off the barge by a single portable crane and popped neatly in place.  Why?  Because we have MUCH better cranes today.<br>
<br>
Using the past experiences of the nuclear industry to predict the future is deeply misguided, sadly.<br>
<br>
<br>
As for the utility owners?  Hey, these are the idiots who built nothing but gas-fired plants for 12 years, and are now shocked that gas is more expensive.  &lt;sigh&gt;  What geniuses.<br>
<br>
