<br>
Nuclear is reliable and immune to icestorms, tornados, bugs, and birdcrap, all environmental factors that can degrade performance.  You can bury a nuke plant flush with the ground- try that with your windmill, which you might as well, when it's calm out. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 178<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/4/03 9:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=159.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: WINDMILLS?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Windmills are for Luddites.<br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
That's not really true.  Everything has advantages and disadvantages and need to be weighed before making judgments.<br>
<br>
Wind only produces waste during construction and decomissioning.  They have a zero daily operating cost (no people required), a variable maintenance cost, and a decent construction cost.<br>
<br>
However, it does have reliability issues.  Lack of wind for an extended period of time will create problems if there is no backup.  Also, wind turbines are particularly vulnerable to severe weather conditions.  So we probably do not want to use them as a base load source.  However, they would make good peaking capacity generation.<br>
<br>
Wind has its place.  I do not believe it to be base load because I feel it needs to be available 100% of the time under any statistically significant factor.  However, it can provide extra over-capacity power for more localized areas during peaking conditions. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25>Energy and the Environment</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.244<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

